\n\nSTDERR:\n<|\">,tool_call_id:<|\">setup_dir<|\">}<tool_response|><turn|><|channel>thought\nOkay, I will create a Wayland C program that displays a spinning gray cube. Since writing a full Wayland client with OpenGL/EGL from scratch is very complex and requires many dependencies (wayland-client, wayland-egl, mesa, etc.), I'll aim for a solution that uses `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl` to set up a surface and use OpenGL for rendering.\n\nWait, a \"simple\" Wayland program usually involves:\n1. Connecting to the Wayland display.\n2. Getting the registry.\n3. Binding to `wl_compositor`, `wl_shell` (deprecated) or `xdg_shell`. I'll use `xdg-shell`.\n4. Setting up a surface and a buffer.\n5. Using EGL to get an OpenGL context.\n6. Rendering the cube.\n\nActually, for a single-file \"wayland c program\" that is easy to compile, using `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl` is the standard way. I'll also need `libwayland-egl`.\n\nLet's check what libraries are available on the system.<channel|><|tool_call>call:run_shell_command{command:<|\"|>pkg-config --list-all | grep wayland<|\"|>,tool_call_id:<|\"|>check_libs<|\"|>}<|tool_response|>response:run_shell_command{result:<|\">EXIT_CODE: 0\nSTDOUT:\ngtk4-wayland                   GTK - GTK Graphical UI Library\nwayland-client                 Wayland Client - Wayland client side library\nwayland-cursor                 Wayland Cursor - Wayland cursor helper library\nwayland-egl                    wayland-egl - Frontend wayland-egl library\nwayland-server                 Wayland Server - Server side implementation of the Wayland protocol\nwayland-protocols              Wayland Protocols - Wayland protocol files\nwayland-scanner                Wayland Scanner - Wayland scanner\nxwaylandproto                  XwaylandProto - Xwayland extension headers\n\nSTDERR:\n<|\">,tool_call_id:<|\">check_libs<|\">}<tool_response|><turn|><|channel>thought\nOkay, `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl` are available. I also likely need `egl` and `gl`.\n\nI'll create a directory `wayland_cube` and then create the C file and the shell script.\n\nSince writing a full EGL/Wayland setup is quite long, I will aim for a concise but complete version.\n\nPlan:\n1. `cube.c`: The Wayland/OpenGL code.\n2. `compile_cube.sh`: A script to compile it using `pkg-config`.\n\nLet's start by writing the `cube.c`.\n\nI'll use `xdg-shell` for the windowing.\n\nWait, I need to make sure I have all necessary headers.\nTypical include path:\n```c\n#include <wayland-client.h>\n#include <wayland-egl.h>\n#include <egl/egl.h>\n#include <GL/gl.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <math.h>\n#include <time.h>\n#include <unistd.h>\n#include <xwayland/xdg-shell-client-protocol.h> // This might not be standard, I should use the generated headers if needed or just assume xdg-shell is available via wayland-protocols\n```\n\nActually, `xdg-shell` requires generating glue code from XML files usually.\nI'll try to find where `xdg-shell.xml` is or if I can just use `wayland-client` and a simple buffer if I don't want to deal with xdg-shell complexity in a single snippet, but xdg-shell is the modern way.\n\nActually, I'll write a version that uses `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl`.\n\nLet's try a simpler approach first: I will write a C file that:\n1. Connects to Wayland.\n2. Uses `wl_compositor` to create a surface.\n3. Uses `xdg_shell` to make it a window (I'll need to generate the xdg-shell glue if I want to be thorough, but often people just include the generated headers).\n\nActually, many systems have `xdg-shell` headers installed, or you can generate them.\nLet's see if `wayland-protocols` is installed. Yes, it was in the list.\n\nI'll write a complete `cube.c`. I will use a simplified approach if possible, but for a \"spinning cube\" it really needs OpenGL.\n\nWait, I can use `GLFW` if it's available, but the prompt asks for \"a wayland c program\", which usually implies using the Wayland API directly.\n