 c program\" that is easy to compile, using `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl` is the standard way. I'll also need `libwayland-egl`.\n\nLet's check what libraries are available on the system.<channel|><|tool_call>call:run_shell_command{command:<|\"|>pkg-config --list-all | grep wayland<|\"|>,tool_call_id:<|\"|>check_libs<|\"|>}<|tool_response|>response:run_shell_command{result:<|\">EXIT_CODE: 0\nSTDOUT:\ngtk4-wayland                   GTK - GTK Graphical UI Library\nwayland-client                 Wayland Client - Wayland client side library\nwayland-cursor                 Wayland Cursor - Wayland cursor helper library\nwayland-egl                    wayland-egl - Frontend wayland-egl library\nwayland-server                 Wayland Server - Server side implementation of the Wayland protocol\nwayland-protocols              Wayland Protocols - Wayland protocol files\nwayland-scanner                Wayland Scanner - Wayland scanner\nxwaylandproto                  XwaylandProto - Xwayland extension headers\n\nSTDERR:\n<|\">,tool_call_id:<|\">check_libs<|\">}<tool_response|><turn|><|channel>thought\nOkay, `wayland-client` and `wayland-egl` are available. I also likely need `egl` and `gl`.\n\nI'll create a directory `wayland_cube` and then create the C file and the shell script.\n\nSince writing a full EGL/Wayland setup is quite long, I will aim for a concise but complete version.\n\nPlan:\n1. `cube.c`: The Wayland/OpenGL code.\n2. `compile_cube.sh`: A script to compile it using `pkg-config`.\n\nLet's start by writing the `cube.c`.\n\nI'll use `xdg-shell` for the windowing.\n\nWait, I need to make sure I have all necessary headers.\nTypical include path:\n```c\n#include <wayland-client.h>\n#include <wayland-egl.h>\n#include <egl/egl.h>\n#include <GL/gl.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <math.h>\n#include <time.h>\n#include <unistd.h>\n#include <xwayland/xdg-shell-client-protocol.h> // This might not be standard, I should use the gen